One of the leading aspirants for the national chairmanship of the ruling All Progressives Congress (APC), Senator Mohammed Sani Musa, has held consultations with Ekiti State Governor Kayode Fayemi. The aspirant was in Ado-Ekiti, the state capital, in continuation of his consultations with party leaders and stakeholders. Musa unveiled his mission and blueprint for the party as a prerequisite in sustaining President Muhammadu Buhari’s legacy and ideology for the party. The aspirant noted that President Buhari has committed so much effort in making the APC a national party for all and a force to reckon with. He stressed that it is necessary to make APC a vibrant democratic institution that grooms leaders, formulate policies and win elections.   Oil, gas operators must account for impacts on environment,…     Wike: It’s time for stomach infrastructure in Rivers     Constitution Review: How lawmakers voted   “It is my view that when those elected in government are doing their job, political parties should be busy working: organising retreats, exchange programmes, party conferences and peer reviews. “These, in my candid opinion, are more important than only waiting for elections or congress periods to surface. “In addition to this, one of the cardinal focal points that is dear to me personally is to strive to adapt to this affiliative and participatory system where everyone will have a sense of belonging in the party,” Musa said while briefing Fayemi. The governor said prior to Musa’s visit, he had been inundated with calls and accused, alongside another governor, that he was one of those pushing for the senator’s name to become APC National Chairman of the party. He praised his visitor, saying Musa’s pedigree and antecedents convinced him that he possesses the requisite leadership qualities to lead the APC and sustain the party’s electoral fortunes.